3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* dns_lookup 3
6/* SUMMARY
7/* domain name service lookup
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #include <dns.h>
10/*
11/* int dns_lookup(name, type, rflags, list, fqdn, why)
12/* const char *name;
13/* unsigned type;
14/* unsigned rflags;
15/* DNS_RR **list;
16/* VSTRING *fqdn;
17/* VSTRING *why;
18/*
19/* int dns_lookup_l(name, rflags, list, fqdn, why, lflags, ltype, ...)
20/* const char *name;
21/* unsigned rflags;
22/* DNS_RR **list;
23/* VSTRING *fqdn;
24/* VSTRING *why;
25/* int lflags;
26/* unsigned ltype;
27/*
28/* int dns_lookup_v(name, rflags, list, fqdn, why, lflags, ltype)
29/* const char *name;
30/* unsigned rflags;
31/* DNS_RR **list;
32/* VSTRING *fqdn;
33/* VSTRING *why;
34/* int lflags;
35/* unsigned *ltype;
36/* AUXILIARY FUNCTIONS
37/* extern int var_dns_ncache_ttl_fix;
38/*
39/* int dns_lookup_r(name, type, rflags, list, fqdn, why, rcode)
40/* const char *name;
41/* unsigned type;
42/* unsigned rflags;
43/* DNS_RR **list;
44/* VSTRING *fqdn;
45/* VSTRING *why;
46/* int *rcode;
47/*
48/* int dns_lookup_rl(name, rflags, list, fqdn, why, rcode, lflags,
49/* ltype, ...)
50/* const char *name;
51/* unsigned rflags;
52/* DNS_RR **list;
53/* VSTRING *fqdn;
54/* VSTRING *why;
55/* int *rcode;
56/* int lflags;
57/* unsigned ltype;
58/*
59/* int dns_lookup_rv(name, rflags, list, fqdn, why, rcode, lflags,
60/* ltype)
61/* const char *name;
62/* unsigned rflags;
63/* DNS_RR **list;
64/* VSTRING *fqdn;
65/* VSTRING *why;
66/* int *rcode;
67/* int lflags;
68/* unsigned *ltype;
69/*
70/* int dns_lookup_x(name, type, rflags, list, fqdn, why, rcode, lflags)
71/* const char *name;
72/* unsigned type;
73/* unsigned rflags;
74/* DNS_RR **list;
75/* VSTRING *fqdn;
76/* VSTRING *why;
77/* int *rcode;
78/* unsigned lflags;
79/* DESCRIPTION
80/* dns_lookup() looks up DNS resource records. When requested to
81/* look up data other than type CNAME, it will follow a limited
82/* number of CNAME indirections. All result names (including
83/* null terminator) will fit a buffer of size DNS_NAME_LEN.
84/* All name results are validated by \fIvalid_hostname\fR();
85/* an invalid name is reported as a DNS_INVAL result, while
86/* malformed replies are reported as transient errors.
87/*
88/* dns_lookup_l() and dns_lookup_v() allow the user to specify
89/* a list of resource types.
90/*
91/* dns_lookup_x, dns_lookup_r(), dns_lookup_rl() and dns_lookup_rv()
92/* accept or return additional information.
93/*
94/* The var_dns_ncache_ttl_fix variable controls a workaround
95/* for res_search(3) implementations that break the
96/* DNS_REQ_FLAG_NCACHE_TTL feature. The workaround does not
97/* support EDNS0 or DNSSEC, but it should be sufficient for
98/* DNSBL/DNSWL lookups.
99/* INPUTS
100/* .ad
101/* .fi
102/* .IP name
103/* The name to be looked up in the domain name system.
104/* This name must pass the valid_hostname() test; it
105/* must not be an IP address.
106/* .IP type
107/* The resource record type to be looked up (T_A, T_MX etc.).
108/* .IP rflags
109/* Resolver flags. These are a bitwise OR of:
110/* .RS
111/* .IP RES_DEBUG
112/* Print debugging information.
113/* .IP RES_DNSRCH
114/* Search local domain and parent domains.
115/* .IP RES_DEFNAMES
116/* Append local domain to unqualified names.
117/* .IP RES_USE_DNSSEC
118/* Request DNSSEC validation. This flag is silently ignored
119/* when the system stub resolver API, resolver(3), does not
120/* implement DNSSEC.
121/* .RE
122/* .IP lflags
123/* Flags that control the operation of the dns_lookup*()
124/* functions. DNS_REQ_FLAG_NONE requests no special processing.
125/* Otherwise, specify one or more of the following:
126/* .RS
127/* .IP DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_INVAL
128/* This flag is used by dns_lookup_l() and dns_lookup_v().
129/* Invoke dns_lookup() for the resource types in the order as
130/* specified, and return when dns_lookup() returns DNS_INVAL.
131/* .IP DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_NULLMX
132/* This flag is used by dns_lookup_l() and dns_lookup_v().
133/* Invoke dns_lookup() for the resource types in the order as
134/* specified, and return when dns_lookup() returns DNS_NULLMX.
135/* .IP DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_MX_POLICY
136/* This flag is used by dns_lookup_l() and dns_lookup_v().
137/* Invoke dns_lookup() for the resource types in the order as
138/* specified, and return when dns_lookup() returns DNS_POLICY
139/* for an MX query.
140/* .IP DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_OK
141/* This flag is used by dns_lookup_l() and dns_lookup_v().
142/* Invoke dns_lookup() for the resource types in the order as
143/* specified, and return when dns_lookup() returns DNS_OK.
144/* .IP DNS_REQ_FLAG_NCACHE_TTL
145/* When the lookup result status is DNS_NOTFOUND, return the
146/* SOA record(s) from the authority section in the reply, if
147/* available. The per-record reply TTL specifies how long the
148/* DNS_NOTFOUND answer is valid. The caller should pass the
149/* record(s) to dns_rr_free().
150/* .RE
151/* .IP ltype
152/* The resource record types to be looked up. In the case of
153/* dns_lookup_l(), this is a null-terminated argument list.
154/* In the case of dns_lookup_v(), this is a null-terminated
155/* integer array.
156/* OUTPUTS
157/* .ad
158/* .fi
159/* .IP list
160/* A null pointer, or a pointer to a variable that receives a
161/* list of requested resource records.
162/* .IP fqdn
163/* A null pointer, or storage for the fully-qualified domain
164/* name found for \fIname\fR.
165/* .IP why
166/* A null pointer, or storage for the reason for failure.
167/* .IP rcode
168/* Pointer to storage for the reply RCODE value. This gives
169/* more detailed information than DNS_FAIL, DNS_RETRY, etc.
170/* DIAGNOSTICS
171/* dns_lookup() returns one of the following codes and sets the
172/* \fIwhy\fR argument accordingly:
173/* .IP DNS_OK
174/* The DNS query succeeded.
175/* .IP DNS_POLICY
176/* The DNS query succeeded, but the answer did not pass the
177/* policy filter.
178/* .IP DNS_NOTFOUND
179/* The DNS query succeeded; the requested information was not found.
180/* .IP DNS_NULLMX
181/* The DNS query succeeded; the requested service is unavailable.
182/* This is returned when the list argument is not a null
183/* pointer, and an MX lookup result contains a null server
184/* name (so-called "nullmx" record).
185/* .IP DNS_INVAL
186/* The DNS query succeeded; the result failed the valid_hostname() test.
187/*
188/* NOTE: the valid_hostname() test is skipped for results that
189/* the caller suppresses explicitly. For example, when the
190/* caller requests MX record lookup but specifies a null
191/* resource record list argument, no syntax check will be done
192/* for MX server names.
193/* .IP DNS_RETRY
194/* The query failed, or the reply was malformed.
195/* The problem is considered transient.
196/* .IP DNS_FAIL
197/* The query failed.
198/* BUGS
199/* dns_lookup() implements a subset of all possible resource types:
200/* CNAME, MX, A, and some records with similar formatting requirements.
201/* It is unwise to specify the T_ANY wildcard resource type.
202/*
203/* It takes a surprising amount of code to accomplish what appears
204/* to be a simple task. Later versions of the mail system may implement
205/* their own DNS client software.
206/* SEE ALSO
207/* dns_rr(3) resource record memory and list management
208/* LICENSE
209/* .ad
210/* .fi
211/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
212/* AUTHOR(S)
213/* Wietse Venema
214/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
215/* P.O. Box 704
216/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
217/*
218/* Wietse Venema
219/* Google, Inc.
220/* 111 8th Avenue
221/* New York, NY 10011, USA
222/*--*/

250 /*
251 * Structure to keep track of things while decoding a name server reply.
252 */
253#define DEF_DNS_REPLY_SIZE 4096 /* in case we're using TCP */
254#define MAX_DNS_REPLY_SIZE 65536 /* in case we're using TCP */
255#define MAX_DNS_QUERY_SIZE 2048 /* XXX */
256
257typedef struct DNS_REPLY {
258 unsigned char *buf; /* raw reply data */
259 size_t buf_len; /* reply buffer length */
260 int rcode; /* unfiltered reply code */
261 int dnssec_ad; /* DNSSEC AD bit */
262 int query_count; /* number of queries */
263 int answer_count; /* number of answers */
264 int auth_count; /* number of authority records */
265 unsigned char *query_start; /* start of query data */
266 unsigned char *answer_start; /* start of answer data */
267 unsigned char *end; /* first byte past reply */
268} DNS_REPLY;
269
270 /*
271 * Test/set primitives to determine if the reply buffer contains a server
272 * response. We use this when the caller requests DNS_REQ_FLAG_NCACHE_TTL,
273 * and the DNS server replies that the requested record does not exist.
274 */
275#define TEST_HAVE_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(r) ((r)->end > (r)->buf)
276#define SET_HAVE_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(r, l) ((r)->end = (r)->buf + (l))
277#define SET_NO_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(r) ((r)->end = (r)->buf)
278
279#define INET_ADDR_LEN 4 /* XXX */
280#define INET6_ADDR_LEN 16 /* XXX */

284static int
285res_ninit(res_state res)
286{
287 int error;
288
289 if ((error = res_init()) < 0)
290 return error;
291
292 *res = _res;
293 return error;
294}

315 /*
316 * To improve postscreen's whitelisting support, we need to know how long a
317 * DNSBL "not found" answer is valid. The 2010 implementation assumed it was
318 * valid for 3600 seconds. That is too long by 2015 standards.
319 *
320 * Instead of guessing, Postfix 3.1 and later implement RFC 2308 (DNS NCACHE),
321 * where a DNS server provides the TTL of a "not found" response as the TTL
322 * of an SOA record in the authority section.
323 *
324 * Unfortunately, the res_search() and res_query() API gets in the way. These
325 * functions overload their result value, the server reply length, and
326 * return -1 when the requested record does not exist. With libbind-based
327 * implementations, the server response is still available in an application
328 * buffer, thanks to the promise that res_query() and res_search() invoke
329 * res_send(), which returns the full server response even if the requested
330 * record does not exist.
331 *
332 * If this promise is broken (for example, res_search() does not call
333 * res_send(), but some non-libbind implementation that updates the
334 * application buffer only when the requested record exists), then we have a
335 * way out by setting the var_dns_ncache_ttl_fix variable. This enables a
336 * limited res_query() clone that should be sufficient for DNSBL / DNSWL
337 * lookups.
338 *
339 * The libunbound API does not comingle the reply length and reply status
340 * information, but that will have to wait until it is safe to make
341 * libunbound a mandatory dependency for Postfix.
342 */
343
344/* dns_res_query - a res_query() clone that can return negative replies */
345
346static int dns_res_query(res_state res, const char *name, int class, int type,
347 unsigned char *answer, int anslen)
348{
349 unsigned char msg_buf[MAX_DNS_QUERY_SIZE];
350 HEADER *reply_header = (HEADER *) answer;
351 int len;
352
353 /*
354 * Differences with res_query() from libbind:
355 *
356 * - This function returns a positive server reply length not only in case
357 * of success, but in all cases where a server reply is available that
358 * passes the preliminary checks in res_send().
359 *
360 * - This function clears h_errno in case of success. The caller must use
361 * h_errno instead of the return value to decide if the lookup was
362 * successful.
363 *
364 * - No support for EDNS0 and DNSSEC (including turning off EDNS0 after
365 * error). That should be sufficient for DNS reputation lookups where the
366 * reply contains a small number of IP addresses. TXT records are out of
367 * scope for this workaround.
368 */
369 reply_header->rcode = NOERROR;
370
371#define NO_MKQUERY_DATA_BUF ((unsigned char *) 0)
372#define NO_MKQUERY_DATA_LEN ((int) 0)
373#define NO_MKQUERY_NEWRR ((unsigned char *) 0)
374
375 if ((len = res_nmkquery(res, QUERY, name, class, type, NO_MKQUERY_DATA_BUF,
376 NO_MKQUERY_DATA_LEN, NO_MKQUERY_NEWRR, msg_buf, sizeof(msg_buf))) < 0) {
377 SET_H_ERRNO(NO_RECOVERY);
378 if (msg_verbose)
379 msg_info("res_mkquery() failed");
380 return (len);
381 } else if ((len = res_nsend(res, msg_buf, len, answer, anslen)) < 0) {
382 SET_H_ERRNO(TRY_AGAIN);
383 if (msg_verbose)
384 msg_info("res_send() failed");
385 return (len);
386 } else {
387 switch (reply_header->rcode) {
388 case NXDOMAIN:
389 SET_H_ERRNO(HOST_NOT_FOUND);
390 break;
391 case NOERROR:
392 if (reply_header->ancount != 0)
393 SET_H_ERRNO(0);
394 else
395 SET_H_ERRNO(NO_DATA);
396 break;
397 case SERVFAIL:
398 SET_H_ERRNO(TRY_AGAIN);
399 break;
400 default:
401 SET_H_ERRNO(NO_RECOVERY);
402 break;
403 }
404 return (len);
405 }
406}

408/* dns_res_search - res_search() that can return negative replies */
409
410static int dns_res_search(res_state res, const char *name, int class, int type,
411 unsigned char *answer, int anslen, int keep_notfound)
412{
413 int len;
414
415 /*
416 * Differences with res_search() from libbind:
417 *
418 * - With a non-zero keep_notfound argument, this function returns a
419 * positive server reply length not only in case of success, but also in
420 * case of a "notfound" reply status. The keep_notfound argument is
421 * usually zero, which allows us to avoid an unnecessary memset() call in
422 * the most common use case.
423 *
424 * - This function clears h_errno in case of success. The caller must use
425 * h_errno instead of the return value to decide if a lookup was
426 * successful.
427 */
428#define NOT_FOUND_H_ERRNO(he) ((he) == HOST_NOT_FOUND || (he) == NO_DATA)
429
430 if (keep_notfound)
431 /* Prepare for returning a null-padded server reply. */
432 memset(answer, 0, anslen);
433 len = res_nquery(res, name, class, type, answer, anslen);
434 if (len > 0) {
435 SET_H_ERRNO(0);
436 } else if (keep_notfound && NOT_FOUND_H_ERRNO(h_errno)) {
437 /* Expect to return a null-padded server reply. */
438 len = anslen;
439 }
440 return (len);
441}
442
443/* dns_query - query name server and pre-parse the reply */
444
445
446static int dns_query(const char *name, int type, unsigned flags,
447 DNS_REPLY *reply, VSTRING *why, unsigned lflags)
448{
449 HEADER *reply_header;
450 int len;
451 unsigned long saved_options;
452 /* For efficiency, we are not called from multiple threads */
453 static struct __res_state res;
454 int keep_notfound = (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_NCACHE_TTL);
455
456 /*
457 * Initialize the reply buffer.
458 */
459 if (reply->buf == 0) {
460 reply->buf = (unsigned char *) mymalloc(DEF_DNS_REPLY_SIZE);
461 reply->buf_len = DEF_DNS_REPLY_SIZE;
462 }
463
464 /*
465 * Initialize the name service.
466 */
467 if ((res.options & RES_INIT) == 0 && res_ninit(&res) < 0) {
468 if (why)
469 vstring_strcpy(why, "Name service initialization failure");
470 return (DNS_FAIL);
471 }
472
473 /*
474 * Set search options: debugging, parent domain search, append local
475 * domain. Do not allow the user to control other features.
476 */
477#define USER_FLAGS (RES_DEBUG | RES_DNSRCH | RES_DEFNAMES | RES_USE_DNSSEC)
478
479 if ((flags & USER_FLAGS) != flags)
480 msg_panic("dns_query: bad flags: %d", flags);
481
482 /*
483 * Set extra options that aren't exposed to the application.
484 */
485#define XTRA_FLAGS (RES_USE_EDNS0)
486
487 if (flags & RES_USE_DNSSEC)
488 flags |= RES_USE_EDNS0;
489
490 /*
491 * Save and restore resolver options that we overwrite, to avoid
492 * surprising behavior in other code that also invokes the resolver.
493 */
494#define SAVE_FLAGS (USER_FLAGS | XTRA_FLAGS)
495
496 saved_options = (res.options & SAVE_FLAGS);
497
498 /*
499 * Perform the lookup. Claim that the information cannot be found if and
500 * only if the name server told us so.
501 */
502 for (;;) {
503 res.options &= ~saved_options;
504 res.options |= flags;
505 if (keep_notfound && var_dns_ncache_ttl_fix) {
506 len = dns_res_query(&res, (char *) name, C_IN, type, reply->buf,
507 reply->buf_len);
508 } else {
509 len = dns_res_search(&res, (char *) name, C_IN, type, reply->buf,
510 reply->buf_len, keep_notfound);
511 }
512 res.options &= ~flags;
513 res.options |= saved_options;
514 reply_header = (HEADER *) reply->buf;
515 reply->rcode = reply_header->rcode;
516 if (h_errno != 0) {
517 if (why)
518 vstring_sprintf(why, "Host or domain name not found. "
519 "Name service error for name=%s type=%s: %s",
520 name, dns_strtype(type), dns_strerror(h_errno));
521 if (msg_verbose)
522 msg_info("dns_query: %s (%s): %s",
523 name, dns_strtype(type), dns_strerror(h_errno));
524 switch (h_errno) {
525 case NO_RECOVERY:
526 return (DNS_FAIL);
527 case HOST_NOT_FOUND:
528 case NO_DATA:
529 if (keep_notfound)
530 break;
531 SET_NO_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(reply);
532 return (DNS_NOTFOUND);
533 default:
534 return (DNS_RETRY);
535 }
536 } else {
537 if (msg_verbose)
538 msg_info("dns_query: %s (%s): OK", name, dns_strtype(type));
539 }
540
541 if (reply_header->tc == 0 || reply->buf_len >= MAX_DNS_REPLY_SIZE)
542 break;
543 reply->buf = (unsigned char *)
544 myrealloc((void *) reply->buf, 2 * reply->buf_len);
545 reply->buf_len *= 2;
546 }
547
548 /*
549 * Future proofing. If this reaches the panic call, then some code change
550 * introduced a bug.
551 */
552 if (len < 0)
553 msg_panic("dns_query: bad length %d (h_errno=%s)",
554 len, dns_strerror(h_errno));
555
556 /*
557 * Paranoia.
558 */
559 if (len > reply->buf_len) {
560 msg_warn("reply length %d > buffer length %d for name=%s type=%s",
561 len, (int) reply->buf_len, name, dns_strtype(type));
562 len = reply->buf_len;
563 }
564
565 /*
566 * Initialize the reply structure. Some structure members are filled on
567 * the fly while the reply is being parsed. Coerce AD bit to boolean.
568 */
569#if RES_USE_DNSSEC != 0
570 reply->dnssec_ad = (flags & RES_USE_DNSSEC) ? !!reply_header->ad : 0;
571#else
572 reply->dnssec_ad = 0;
573#endif
574 SET_HAVE_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(reply, len);
575 reply->query_start = reply->buf + sizeof(HEADER);
576 reply->answer_start = 0;
577 reply->query_count = ntohs(reply_header->qdcount);
578 reply->answer_count = ntohs(reply_header->ancount);
579 reply->auth_count = ntohs(reply_header->nscount);
580 if (msg_verbose > 1)
581 msg_info("dns_query: reply len=%d ancount=%d nscount=%d",
582 len, reply->answer_count, reply->auth_count);
583
584 /*
585 * Future proofing. If this reaches the panic call, then some code change
586 * introduced a bug.
587 */
588 if (h_errno == 0) {
589 return (DNS_OK);
590 } else if (keep_notfound) {
591 return (DNS_NOTFOUND);
592 } else {
593 msg_panic("dns_query: unexpected reply status: %s",
594 dns_strerror(h_errno));
595 }
596}

598/* dns_skip_query - skip query data in name server reply */
599
600static int dns_skip_query(DNS_REPLY *reply)
601{
602 int query_count = reply->query_count;
603 unsigned char *pos = reply->query_start;
604 int len;
605
606 /*
607 * For each query, skip over the domain name and over the fixed query
608 * data.
609 */
610 while (query_count-- > 0) {
611 if (pos >= reply->end)
612 return DNS_RETRY;
613 len = dn_skipname(pos, reply->end);
614 if (len < 0)
615 return (DNS_RETRY);
616 pos += len + QFIXEDSZ;
617 }
618 reply->answer_start = pos;
619 return (DNS_OK);
620}

622/* dns_get_fixed - extract fixed data from resource record */
623
624static int dns_get_fixed(unsigned char *pos, DNS_FIXED *fixed)
625{
626 GETSHORT(fixed->type, pos);
627 GETSHORT(fixed->class, pos);
628 GETLONG(fixed->ttl, pos);
629 GETSHORT(fixed->length, pos);
630
631 if (fixed->class != C_IN) {
632 msg_warn("dns_get_fixed: bad class: %u", fixed->class);
633 return (DNS_RETRY);
634 }
635 return (DNS_OK);
636}

638/* valid_rr_name - validate hostname in resource record */
639
640static int valid_rr_name(const char *name, const char *location,
641 unsigned type, DNS_REPLY *reply)
642{
643 char temp[DNS_NAME_LEN];
644 char *query_name;
645 int len;
646 char *gripe;
647 int result;
648
649 /*
650 * People aren't supposed to specify numeric names where domain names are
651 * required, but it "works" with some mailers anyway, so people complain
652 * when software doesn't bend over backwards.
653 */
654#define PASS_NAME 1
655#define REJECT_NAME 0
656
657 if (valid_hostaddr(name, DONT_GRIPE)) {
658 result = PASS_NAME;
659 gripe = "numeric domain name";
660 } else if (!valid_hostname(name, DO_GRIPE)) {
661 result = REJECT_NAME;
662 gripe = "malformed domain name";
663 } else {
664 result = PASS_NAME;
665 gripe = 0;
666 }
667
668 /*
669 * If we have a gripe, show some context, including the name used in the
670 * query and the type of reply that we're looking at.
671 */
672 if (gripe) {
673 len = dn_expand(reply->buf, reply->end, reply->query_start,
674 temp, DNS_NAME_LEN);
675 query_name = (len < 0 ? "*unparsable*" : temp);
676 msg_warn("%s in %s of %s record for %s: %.100s",
677 gripe, location, dns_strtype(type), query_name, name);
678 }
679 return (result);
680}
681
682/* dns_get_rr - extract resource record from name server reply */
683
684static int dns_get_rr(DNS_RR **list, const char *orig_name, DNS_REPLY *reply,
685 unsigned char *pos, char *rr_name,
686 DNS_FIXED *fixed)
687{
688 char temp[DNS_NAME_LEN];
689 char *tempbuf = temp;
690 UINT32_TYPE soa_buf[5];
691 int comp_len;
692 ssize_t data_len;
693 unsigned pref = 0;
694 unsigned char *src;
695 unsigned char *dst;
696 int ch;
697
698#define MIN2(a, b) ((unsigned)(a) < (unsigned)(b) ? (a) : (b))
699
700 *list = 0;
701
702 switch (fixed->type) {
703 default:
704 msg_panic("dns_get_rr: don't know how to extract resource type %s",
705 dns_strtype(fixed->type));
706 case T_CNAME:
707 case T_DNAME:
708 case T_MB:
709 case T_MG:
710 case T_MR:
711 case T_NS:
712 case T_PTR:
713 if (dn_expand(reply->buf, reply->end, pos, temp, sizeof(temp)) < 0)
714 return (DNS_RETRY);
715 if (!valid_rr_name(temp, "resource data", fixed->type, reply))
716 return (DNS_INVAL);
717 data_len = strlen(temp) + 1;
718 break;
719 case T_MX:
720 GETSHORT(pref, pos);
721 if (dn_expand(reply->buf, reply->end, pos, temp, sizeof(temp)) < 0)
722 return (DNS_RETRY);
723 /* Don't even think of returning an invalid hostname to the caller. */
724 if (*temp == 0)
725 return (DNS_NULLMX); /* TODO: descriptive text */
726 if (!valid_rr_name(temp, "resource data", fixed->type, reply))
727 return (DNS_INVAL);
728 data_len = strlen(temp) + 1;
729 break;
730 case T_A:
731 if (fixed->length != INET_ADDR_LEN) {
732 msg_warn("extract_answer: bad address length: %d", fixed->length);
733 return (DNS_RETRY);
734 }
735 if (fixed->length > sizeof(temp))
736 msg_panic("dns_get_rr: length %d > DNS_NAME_LEN",
737 fixed->length);
738 memcpy(temp, pos, fixed->length);
739 data_len = fixed->length;
740 break;
741#ifdef T_AAAA
742 case T_AAAA:
743 if (fixed->length != INET6_ADDR_LEN) {
744 msg_warn("extract_answer: bad address length: %d", fixed->length);
745 return (DNS_RETRY);
746 }
747 if (fixed->length > sizeof(temp))
748 msg_panic("dns_get_rr: length %d > DNS_NAME_LEN",
749 fixed->length);
750 memcpy(temp, pos, fixed->length);
751 data_len = fixed->length;
752 break;
753#endif
754
755 /*
756 * We impose the same length limit here as for DNS names. However,
757 * see T_TLSA discussion below.
758 */
759 case T_TXT:
760 data_len = MIN2(pos[0] + 1, MIN2(fixed->length + 1, sizeof(temp)));
761 for (src = pos + 1, dst = (unsigned char *) (temp);
762 dst < (unsigned char *) (temp) + data_len - 1; /* */ ) {
763 ch = *src++;
764 *dst++ = (ISPRINT(ch) ? ch : ' ');
765 }
766 *dst = 0;
767 break;
768
769 /*
770 * For a full certificate, fixed->length may be longer than
771 * sizeof(tmpbuf) == DNS_NAME_LEN. Since we don't need a decode
772 * buffer, just copy the raw data into the rr.
773 *
774 * XXX Reject replies with bogus length < 3.
775 *
776 * XXX What about enforcing a sane upper bound? The RFC 1035 hard
777 * protocol limit is the RRDATA length limit of 65535.
778 */
779 case T_TLSA:
780 data_len = fixed->length;
781 tempbuf = (char *) pos;
782 break;
783
784 /*
785 * We use the SOA record TTL to determine the negative reply TTL. We
786 * save the time fields in the SOA record for debugging, but for now
787 * we don't bother saving the source host and mailbox information, as
788 * that would require changes to the DNS_RR structure and APIs. See
789 * also code in dns_strrecord().
790 */
791 case T_SOA:
792 comp_len = dn_skipname(pos, reply->end);
793 if (comp_len < 0)
794 return (DNS_RETRY);
795 pos += comp_len;
796 comp_len = dn_skipname(pos, reply->end);
797 if (comp_len < 0)
798 return (DNS_RETRY);
799 pos += comp_len;
800 if (reply->end - pos < sizeof(soa_buf)) {
801 msg_warn("extract_answer: bad SOA length: %d", fixed->length);
802 return (DNS_RETRY);
803 }
804 GETLONG(soa_buf[0], pos); /* Serial */
805 GETLONG(soa_buf[1], pos); /* Refresh */
806 GETLONG(soa_buf[2], pos); /* Retry */
807 GETLONG(soa_buf[3], pos); /* Expire */
808 GETLONG(soa_buf[4], pos); /* Ncache TTL */
809 tempbuf = (char *) soa_buf;
810 data_len = sizeof(soa_buf);
811 break;
812 }
813 *list = dns_rr_create(orig_name, rr_name, fixed->type, fixed->class,
814 fixed->ttl, pref, tempbuf, data_len);
815 return (DNS_OK);
816}

818/* dns_get_alias - extract CNAME from name server reply */
819
820static int dns_get_alias(DNS_REPLY *reply, unsigned char *pos,
821 DNS_FIXED *fixed, char *cname, int c_len)
822{
823 if (fixed->type != T_CNAME)
824 msg_panic("dns_get_alias: bad type %s", dns_strtype(fixed->type));
825 if (dn_expand(reply->buf, reply->end, pos, cname, c_len) < 0)
826 return (DNS_RETRY);
827 if (!valid_rr_name(cname, "resource data", fixed->type, reply))
828 return (DNS_INVAL);
829 return (DNS_OK);
830}
831
832/* dns_get_answer - extract answers from name server reply */
833
834static int dns_get_answer(const char *orig_name, DNS_REPLY *reply, int type,
835 DNS_RR **rrlist, VSTRING *fqdn, char *cname, int c_len,
836 int *maybe_secure)
837{
838 char rr_name[DNS_NAME_LEN];
839 unsigned char *pos;
840 int answer_count = reply->answer_count;
841 int len;
842 DNS_FIXED fixed;
843 DNS_RR *rr;
844 int resource_found = 0;
845 int cname_found = 0;
846 int not_found_status = DNS_NOTFOUND; /* can't happen */
847 int status;
848
849 /*
850 * Initialize. Skip over the name server query if we haven't yet.
851 */
852 if (reply->answer_start == 0)
853 if ((status = dns_skip_query(reply)) < 0)
854 return (status);
855 pos = reply->answer_start;
856
857 /*
858 * Either this, or use a GOTO for emergency exits. The purpose is to
859 * prevent incomplete answers from being passed back to the caller.
860 */
861#define CORRUPT(status) { \
862 if (rrlist && *rrlist) { \
863 dns_rr_free(*rrlist); \
864 *rrlist = 0; \
865 } \
866 return (status); \
867 }
868
869 /*
870 * Iterate over all answers.
871 */
872 while (answer_count-- > 0) {
873
874 /*
875 * Optionally extract the fully-qualified domain name.
876 */
877 if (pos >= reply->end)
878 CORRUPT(DNS_RETRY);
879 len = dn_expand(reply->buf, reply->end, pos, rr_name, DNS_NAME_LEN);
880 if (len < 0)
881 CORRUPT(DNS_RETRY);
882 pos += len;
883
884 /*
885 * Extract the fixed reply data: type, class, ttl, length.
886 */
887 if (pos + RRFIXEDSZ > reply->end)
888 CORRUPT(DNS_RETRY);
889 if ((status = dns_get_fixed(pos, &fixed)) != DNS_OK)
890 CORRUPT(status);
891 if (!valid_rr_name(rr_name, "resource name", fixed.type, reply))
892 CORRUPT(DNS_INVAL);
893 if (fqdn)
894 vstring_strcpy(fqdn, rr_name);
895 if (msg_verbose)
896 msg_info("dns_get_answer: type %s for %s",
897 dns_strtype(fixed.type), rr_name);
898 pos += RRFIXEDSZ;
899
900 /*
901 * Optionally extract the requested resource or CNAME data.
902 */
903 if (pos + fixed.length > reply->end)
904 CORRUPT(DNS_RETRY);
905 if (type == fixed.type || type == T_ANY) { /* requested type */
906 if (rrlist) {
907 if ((status = dns_get_rr(&rr, orig_name, reply, pos, rr_name,
908 &fixed)) == DNS_OK) {
909 resource_found++;
910 rr->dnssec_valid = *maybe_secure ? reply->dnssec_ad : 0;
911 *rrlist = dns_rr_append(*rrlist, rr);
912 } else if (status == DNS_NULLMX) {
913 CORRUPT(status); /* TODO: use better name */
914 } else if (not_found_status != DNS_RETRY)
915 not_found_status = status;
916 } else
917 resource_found++;
918 } else if (fixed.type == T_CNAME) { /* cname resource */
919 cname_found++;
920 if (cname && c_len > 0)
921 if ((status = dns_get_alias(reply, pos, &fixed, cname, c_len)) != DNS_OK)
922 CORRUPT(status);
923 if (!reply->dnssec_ad)
924 *maybe_secure = 0;
925 }
926 pos += fixed.length;
927 }
928
929 /*
930 * See what answer we came up with. Report success when the requested
931 * information was found. Otherwise, when a CNAME was found, report that
932 * more recursion is needed. Otherwise report failure.
933 */
934 if (resource_found)
935 return (DNS_OK);
936 if (cname_found)
937 return (DNS_RECURSE);
938 return (not_found_status);
939}
940
941/* dns_lookup_x - DNS lookup user interface */
942
943int dns_lookup_x(const char *name, unsigned type, unsigned flags,
944 DNS_RR **rrlist, VSTRING *fqdn, VSTRING *why,
945 int *rcode, unsigned lflags)
946{
947 char cname[DNS_NAME_LEN];
948 int c_len = sizeof(cname);
949 static DNS_REPLY reply;
950 int count;
951 int status;
952 int maybe_secure = 1; /* Query name presumed secure */
953 const char *orig_name = name;
954
955 /*
956 * Reset results early. DNS_OK is not the only status that returns
957 * resource records; DNS_NOTFOUND will do that too, if requested.
958 */
959 if (rrlist)
960 *rrlist = 0;
961
962 /*
963 * DJBDNS produces a bogus A record when given a numerical hostname.
964 */
965 if (valid_hostaddr(name, DONT_GRIPE)) {
966 if (why)
967 vstring_sprintf(why,
968 "Name service error for %s: invalid host or domain name",
969 name);
970 if (rcode)
971 *rcode = NXDOMAIN;
972 SET_H_ERRNO(HOST_NOT_FOUND);
973 return (DNS_NOTFOUND);
974 }
975
976 /*
977 * The Linux resolver misbehaves when given an invalid domain name.
978 */
979 if (!valid_hostname(name, DONT_GRIPE)) {
980 if (why)
981 vstring_sprintf(why,
982 "Name service error for %s: invalid host or domain name",
983 name);
984 if (rcode)
985 *rcode = NXDOMAIN;
986 SET_H_ERRNO(HOST_NOT_FOUND);
987 return (DNS_NOTFOUND);
988 }
989
990 /*
991 * Perform the lookup. Follow CNAME chains, but only up to a
992 * pre-determined maximum.
993 */
994 for (count = 0; count < 10; count++) {
995
996 /*
997 * Perform the DNS lookup, and pre-parse the name server reply.
998 */
999 status = dns_query(name, type, flags, &reply, why, lflags);
1000 if (rcode)
1001 *rcode = reply.rcode;
1002 if (status != DNS_OK) {
1003
1004 /*
1005 * If the record does not exist, and we have a copy of the server
1006 * response, try to extract the negative caching TTL for the SOA
1007 * record in the authority section. DO NOT return an error if an
1008 * SOA record is malformed.
1009 */
1010 if (status == DNS_NOTFOUND && TEST_HAVE_DNS_REPLY_PACKET(&reply)
1011 && reply.auth_count > 0) {
1012 reply.answer_count = reply.auth_count; /* XXX TODO: Fix API */
1013 (void) dns_get_answer(orig_name, &reply, T_SOA, rrlist, fqdn,
1014 cname, c_len, &maybe_secure);
1015 }
1016 return (status);
1017 }
1018
1019 /*
1020 * Extract resource records of the requested type. Pick up CNAME
1021 * information just in case the requested data is not found.
1022 */
1023 status = dns_get_answer(orig_name, &reply, type, rrlist, fqdn,
1024 cname, c_len, &maybe_secure);
1025 switch (status) {
1026 default:
1027 if (why)
1028 vstring_sprintf(why, "Name service error for name=%s type=%s: "
1029 "Malformed or unexpected name server reply",
1030 name, dns_strtype(type));
1031 return (status);
1032 case DNS_NULLMX:
1033 if (why)
1034 vstring_sprintf(why, "Domain %s does not accept mail (nullMX)",
1035 name);
1036 SET_H_ERRNO(NO_DATA);
1037 return (status);
1038 case DNS_OK:
1039 if (rrlist && dns_rr_filter_maps) {
1040 if (dns_rr_filter_execute(rrlist) < 0) {
1041 if (why)
1042 vstring_sprintf(why,
1043 "Error looking up name=%s type=%s: "
1044 "Invalid DNS reply filter syntax",
1045 name, dns_strtype(type));
1046 dns_rr_free(*rrlist);
1047 *rrlist = 0;
1048 status = DNS_RETRY;
1049 } else if (*rrlist == 0) {
1050 if (why)
1051 vstring_sprintf(why,
1052 "Error looking up name=%s type=%s: "
1053 "DNS reply filter drops all results",
1054 name, dns_strtype(type));
1055 status = DNS_POLICY;
1056 }
1057 }
1058 return (status);
1059 case DNS_RECURSE:
1060 if (msg_verbose)
1061 msg_info("dns_lookup: %s aliased to %s", name, cname);
1062#if RES_USE_DNSSEC
1063
1064 /*
1065 * Once an intermediate CNAME reply is not validated, all
1066 * consequent RRs are deemed not validated, so we don't ask for
1067 * further DNSSEC replies.
1068 */
1069 if (maybe_secure == 0)
1070 flags &= ~RES_USE_DNSSEC;
1071#endif
1072 name = cname;
1073 }
1074 }
1075 if (why)
1076 vstring_sprintf(why, "Name server loop for %s", name);
1077 msg_warn("dns_lookup: Name server loop for %s", name);
1078 return (DNS_NOTFOUND);
1079}

1081/* dns_lookup_rl - DNS lookup interface with types list */
1082
1083int dns_lookup_rl(const char *name, unsigned flags, DNS_RR **rrlist,
1084 VSTRING *fqdn, VSTRING *why, int *rcode,
1085 int lflags,...)
1086{
1087 va_list ap;
1088 unsigned type, next;
1089 int status = DNS_NOTFOUND;
1090 int hpref_status = INT_MIN;
1091 VSTRING *hpref_rtext = 0;
1092 int hpref_rcode;
1093 int hpref_h_errno;
1094 DNS_RR *rr;
1095
1096 /* Save intermediate highest-priority result. */
1097#define SAVE_HPREF_STATUS() do { \
1098 hpref_status = status; \
1099 if (rcode) \
1100 hpref_rcode = *rcode; \
1101 if (why && status != DNS_OK) \
1102 vstring_strcpy(hpref_rtext ? hpref_rtext : \
1103 (hpref_rtext = vstring_alloc(VSTRING_LEN(why))), \
1104 vstring_str(why)); \
1105 hpref_h_errno = h_errno; \
1106 } while (0)
1107
1108 /* Restore intermediate highest-priority result. */
1109#define RESTORE_HPREF_STATUS() do { \
1110 status = hpref_status; \
1111 if (rcode) \
1112 *rcode = hpref_rcode; \
1113 if (why && status != DNS_OK) \
1114 vstring_strcpy(why, vstring_str(hpref_rtext)); \
1115 SET_H_ERRNO(hpref_h_errno); \
1116 } while (0)
1117
1118 if (rrlist)
1119 *rrlist = 0;
1120 va_start(ap, lflags);
1121 for (type = va_arg(ap, unsigned); type != 0; type = next) {
1122 next = va_arg(ap, unsigned);
1123 if (msg_verbose)
1124 msg_info("lookup %s type %s flags %d",
1125 name, dns_strtype(type), flags);
1126 status = dns_lookup_x(name, type, flags, rrlist ? &rr : (DNS_RR **) 0,
1127 fqdn, why, rcode, lflags);
1128 if (rrlist && rr)
1129 *rrlist = dns_rr_append(*rrlist, rr);
1130 if (status == DNS_OK) {
1131 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_OK)
1132 break;
1133 } else if (status == DNS_INVAL) {
1134 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_INVAL)
1135 break;
1136 } else if (status == DNS_POLICY) {
1137 if (type == T_MX && (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_MX_POLICY))
1138 break;
1139 } else if (status == DNS_NULLMX) {
1140 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_NULLMX)
1141 break;
1142 }
1143 /* XXX Stop after NXDOMAIN error. */
1144 if (next == 0)
1145 break;
1146 if (status >= hpref_status)
1147 SAVE_HPREF_STATUS(); /* save last info */
1148 }
1149 va_end(ap);
1150 if (status < hpref_status)
1151 RESTORE_HPREF_STATUS(); /* else report last info */
1152 if (hpref_rtext)
1153 vstring_free(hpref_rtext);
1154 return (status);
1155}
1156
1157/* dns_lookup_rv - DNS lookup interface with types vector */
1158
1159int dns_lookup_rv(const char *name, unsigned flags, DNS_RR **rrlist,
1160 VSTRING *fqdn, VSTRING *why, int *rcode,
1161 int lflags, unsigned *types)
1162{
1163 unsigned type, next;
1164 int status = DNS_NOTFOUND;
1165 int hpref_status = INT_MIN;
1166 VSTRING *hpref_rtext = 0;
1167 int hpref_rcode;
1168 int hpref_h_errno;
1169 DNS_RR *rr;
1170
1171 if (rrlist)
1172 *rrlist = 0;
1173 for (type = *types++; type != 0; type = next) {
1174 next = *types++;
1175 if (msg_verbose)
1176 msg_info("lookup %s type %s flags %d",
1177 name, dns_strtype(type), flags);
1178 status = dns_lookup_x(name, type, flags, rrlist ? &rr : (DNS_RR **) 0,
1179 fqdn, why, rcode, lflags);
1180 if (rrlist && rr)
1181 *rrlist = dns_rr_append(*rrlist, rr);
1182 if (status == DNS_OK) {
1183 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_OK)
1184 break;
1185 } else if (status == DNS_INVAL) {
1186 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_INVAL)
1187 break;
1188 } else if (status == DNS_POLICY) {
1189 if (type == T_MX && (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_MX_POLICY))
1190 break;
1191 } else if (status == DNS_NULLMX) {
1192 if (lflags & DNS_REQ_FLAG_STOP_NULLMX)
1193 break;
1194 }
1195 /* XXX Stop after NXDOMAIN error. */
1196 if (next == 0)
1197 break;
1198 if (status >= hpref_status)
1199 SAVE_HPREF_STATUS(); /* save last info */
1200 }
1201 if (status < hpref_status)
1202 RESTORE_HPREF_STATUS(); /* else report last info */
1203 if (hpref_rtext)
1204 vstring_free(hpref_rtext);
1205 return (status);
1206}
